         <abstract>
            <p>The high grade bond markets are being buffeted from many sources: the economy is threatening to break out into inflation; the Federal government is adding its needs to those of the private sector at a record rate, and many users of funds are seeking to anticipate their needs. Under these conditions, vigorous fiscal action is needed but is slow in forthcoming. Again monetary policy may be called upon to apply the needed restraint. Use of conventional monetary tools, however, could result in renewed stress upon money and capital markets at even higher rates than present record levels. The use of direct controls is an unwelcome alternative approach. N.B. Please see addendum on page 13.</p>
          </abstract>
